## TL;DR
With Java 21, you can do
```java
public sealed interface Either&lt;A, B&gt; permits Left, Right {}
public record Left&lt;A, B&gt;(A value) implements Either&lt;A, B&gt; {}
public record Right&lt;A, B&gt;(B value) implements Either&lt;A, B&gt; {}
```
```java
public &lt;A,B,R&gt; R match(Either&lt;A,B&gt; a, Function&lt;A,R&gt; left, Function&lt;B,R&gt; right){
    return switch(a){
        case Left&lt;A,B&gt;(A value) -&gt; left.apply(value);
        case Right&lt;A,B&gt;(B value) -&gt; right.apply(value);
    };
}
```
## Long version
In recent Java versions, there have been a lot of additions to the Java language due to [project Amber](https://openjdk.org/projects/amber/) which are useful for that kind of problem.  
Namely, Java added [Records](https://openjdk.org/jeps/395), [sealed classes](https://openjdk.org/jeps/409), [record patterns](https://openjdk.org/jeps/440), [switch patternmatching](https://openjdk.org/jeps/441) and [switch expressions](https://openjdk.org/jeps/361).

Since [Sealed classes have been introduced in Java 17](https://openjdk.org/jeps/409), you can now use these to make an `Either` type. Sealed classes ensure there cannot be any other subclasses.  
In your case, the type system guarantees that your `Either` objects are either `Left` or a `Right` objects but not anything else.

I will adapt [Jon Purdy&#39;s answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/48143514/10871900) with sealed classes.
```java
public sealed interface Either&lt;A, B&gt; permits Left, Right{
    &lt;R&gt; R match(Function&lt;A, R&gt; left, Function&lt;B, R&gt; right);
    static &lt;A, B&gt; Left&lt;A, B&gt; left(A value){
        return new Left&lt;&gt;(value);
    }
    static &lt;A, B&gt; Right&lt;A, B&gt; right(B value){
        return new Right&lt;&gt;(value);
    } 
}

public record Left&lt;A, B&gt;(A value) implements Either&lt;A, B&gt; {

    @Override
    public &lt;R&gt; R match(Function&lt;A, R&gt; left, Function&lt;B, R&gt; right) {
        return left.apply(value());
    }
}

public record Right&lt;A, B&gt;(B value) implements Either&lt;A, B&gt; {

    @Override
    public &lt;R&gt; R match(Function&lt;A, R&gt; left, Function&lt;B, R&gt; right) {
        return right.apply(value());
    }
}
```

I have also added two things for convenience:
- `static` factory methods which can be used for instantiating `Either` objects without the `Left`/`Right` classes
- I have converted `Left`/`Right` classes to [records (available since Java 16)](https://openjdk.org/jeps/395) which are essentially immutable data classes.

These changes allow accessing the value once you know whether it is a `Left` or `Right` object.
With [switch patternmatching](https://openjdk.org/jeps/441) and [record patterns](https://openjdk.org/jeps/440) which will both be finalized in Java 21, you can conveniently `switch` between the `Left` and `Right` type:
```java
Either&lt;L, R&gt; a= ...;
switch(a){
    case Left&lt;L,R&gt;(L value) -&gt; doLeft(value);
    case Right&lt;L,R&gt;(R value) -&gt; doRight(value);
}
```
You can also use [switch expressions](https://openjdk.org/jeps/361) for making this `switch` statement an expression:
```java
Either&lt;L, R&gt; a= ...;
ResultType result = switch(a){
    case Left&lt;L,R&gt;(L value) -&gt; computeLeftResult(value);
    case Right&lt;L,R&gt;(R value) -&gt; computeRightResult(value);
}
```
This is essentially equivalent to the `match` method.

If you prefer that to the `match` method, you can simplify the code:
```java
public sealed interface Either&lt;A, B&gt; permits Left, Right {}

public record Left&lt;A, B&gt;(A value) implements Either&lt;A, B&gt; {}

public record Right&lt;A, B&gt;(B value) implements Either&lt;A, B&gt; {}
```
and you can still match using the `switch` construct as mentioned before:
```java
Either&lt;L, R&gt; a= ...;
ResultType result = switch(a){
    case Left&lt;L,R&gt;(L value) -&gt; computeLeftResult(value);
    case Right&lt;L,R&gt;(R value) -&gt; computeRightResult(value);
}
```

## Alternative: common supertype

If the types naturally belong together can add an interface to both types, you can make that sealed as well:
```java
//please use a better name for your specific use-case
public interface AOrB permits A, B {
    //possible common functionality
}

public class A implements AOrB{
    //specific functionality for A
}

public class B implements AOrB{
    //specific functionality for B
}
```

You can then switch over them like:
```java
public &lt;R&gt; R matchAB(AOrB aOrB, Function&lt;A,R&gt; left, Function&lt;B,R&gt; right){
    return switch(aOrB){
        case A a -&gt; left.apply(a);
        case B b -&gt; right.apply(b);
    };
}
```

In many cases, you might also want to use records for `A` and `B`.

